********************************************************************
* Rescue - Rescue On Fractalus Program
*
* NOTE:  This code assembles to the EXACT same object code found on
*        the original Rescue on Fractalus disk.
*
*        Header for : RESCUE
*        Module size: $5B18  #23320
*        Module CRC : $C4EB06 (Good)
*        Hdr parity : $6B
*        Exec. off  : $0013  #19
*        Data size  : $6000  #24576
*        Edition    : $30  #48
*        Ty/La At/Rv: $11 $81
*        Prog mod, 6809 Obj, re-ent, R/O
*
* Edt/Rev  YYYY/MM/DD  Modified by
* Comment
* ------------------------------------------------------------------
*          1995/07/23  Boisy G. Pitre
* Disassembled at 10:11:57.
*
*          2026/07/20  Codex
* Reverse-engineered and deeply annotated without changing the object code.
*
* ------------------------------------------------------------------
* REVERSE-ENGINEERING OVERVIEW
* ------------------------------------------------------------------
* This is the OS-9/6809 port of Lucasfilm Games' first-person rescue game.
* It is not a conventional tile game.  Every flight frame transforms a small
* height field into the pilot's coordinate system, perspective-projects it,
* clips it, and paints filled mountain facets into a 160x192 four-bit-pixel
* screen.  The cockpit, instruments, ships, pilots, weapons, and damage are
* composited over that generated view.
*
* The main control path is:
*
*   start       OS-9 screen/path setup and asset loading
*   initialize_screen_rows       build scan-line tables and initialize persistent state
*   run_frontend_and_level_progression       title/demo/level-selection and between-level accounting
*   begin_sortie       begin a sortie and draw its fixed cockpit
*   enter_live_sortie       initialize the world and per-sortie simulation state
*   main_frame_first_pass       two rendering/simulation passes per outer game iteration
*   check_secret_key_sequence       recognize a hidden six-key sequence
*   transform_terrain_lattice       rotate/translate the terrain sample lattice
*   render_terrain_view       project, clip, depth-order, and rasterize the terrain
*   update_hostile_objects       update hostile ground/air objects
*   restore_cockpit_borders       restore fixed cockpit edge colors after view drawing
*   blit_backbuffer_to_screen       copy the 12-KiB back buffer to the displayed OS-9 screen
*   L3xxx       cockpit instruments, messages, and display primitives
*   L41xx       sortie state, scoring, and status-message selection
*   L42xx-L46xx rescue, pilot/alien, weapon, and collision state machines
*   update_flight_dynamics       joystick-derived flight dynamics and world integration
*   L53xx-L56xx clipped line/pixel drawing and screen damage effects
*   play_sound_script       interpret compact tone scripts through SS.Tone
*   next_random_byte       table-driven pseudo-random byte generator
*
* SCREEN AND DRAWING MODEL
* ------------------------
* SS.AScrn allocates a 160x192x16-color screen: 80 bytes per scan line, with
* two four-bit pixels packed in each byte.  initialize_screen_rows constructs 192 forward row
* pointers at $0D03 and 96 reverse row pointers at $0E83.  Much of the game
* draws into a 12-KiB work image at $3F47; blit_backbuffer_to_screen temporarily moves the hardware
* stack to that image and uses balanced PULS/PSHU transfers as an aggressively
* unrolled block copier into the OS-9 screen.  Nibble masks such as $F0/$0F and
* color pairs such as $77 are therefore pixel operations, not arithmetic data.
*
* TERRAIN PIPELINE
* ----------------
* transform_terrain_lattice selects an orientation table, rotates and translates 46 terrain sample
* points, derives their procedural height/color samples, and classifies their
* visibility.  project_terrain_vertex performs fixed-point perspective division for a point and
* produces projected coordinates in the $0B3F/$0B9B arrays.  render_terrain_view walks the
* facet topology at $3B6F, rejects hidden or clipped facets, and sends visible
* edges/spans through the $1Dxx-$22xx raster machinery.  Signed shifts, rotates,
* and the restoring divider at divide_fixed_point are fixed-point geometry; they are kept in
* integer form so a 6809 can regenerate the landscape in real time.
*
* FLIGHT, THREATS, AND RESCUE
* ---------------------------
* update_flight_dynamics quantizes joystick motion, applies inertia and altitude limits, rotates
* the horizontal velocity into world coordinates, and advances the camera.
* The phase byte at flight_phase distinguishes active flight from the landing/rescue
* transition.  Hostile emplacements and later kamikaze saucers are maintained
* by the $1Axx object update.  During a rescue, the $42xx-$46xx code sequences
* landing, systems/shields, the approaching figure, airlock timing, human/Ace
* boarding, and the Jaggi attack.  Several meanings in that state machine are
* inferred from message indices, sprite assets, sound calls, and the documented
* play sequence; comments say "appears" where the binary does not prove a name.
*
* INPUT, MESSAGES, SOUND, AND SCORE
* ---------------------------------
* getjoyxy reduces each analog axis to -1/0/+1 and records direction changes.
* pollkybd/readch maintain a small command queue used by check_secret_key_sequence.  Commands cover
* thrust, landing, systems/shields, airlock, and booster docking.  draw_bitmap_text draws
* text from the font and message tables loaded in ROFVAR.  play_sound_script interprets
* compact sound scripts rather than hard-coding each effect.  Score bytes at
* $0CF5-$0CF8 are packed BCD; add_packed_bcd_score formats them for the cockpit, while wrscores
* persists the high-score table in the SCORES side file.
*
* ASSET LAYOUT
* ------------
* ROFVAR supplies messages, font/character maps, geometry, palettes, and lookup
* tables.  PANEL1 is the cockpit image.  BODY, HEADS, LARMS, and LIPS contain the
* layered pilot/Jaggi animation.  The pointer tables built at $2C90/$2C9E/$2CA8
* index variable-sized frames whose first two bytes encode dimensions.
* ------------------------------------------------------------------

                                      nam       Rescue
                                      ttl       Rescue On Fractalus Program

                                    IFP1
                                      use       defsfile
                                    ENDC

* standard paths
stdin                                 equ       0
stdout                                equ       1
stderr                                equ       2

